h the best-selling nautical literature of the time by dramatizing remarkable conditions, from the wonders of unknown lands to storms, shipwrecks, and pirates. She considers James Fenimore Cooper's refashioning of the adventure novel in postcolonial America, and a change in literary poetics toward new frontiers and to the maritime labor and technology of the nineteenth century. Cohen shows how Jules Verne reworked adventures at sea into science fiction; how Melville, Hugo, and Conrad navigated the foggy waters of language and thought; and how detective and spy fiction built on sea fiction's problem-solving devices. She also discusses the transformation of the ocean from a theater of skilled work to an environment of pristine nature and the sublime.A significant literary history, The Novel and the Sea challenges readers to rethink their land-locked assumptions about the novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAddison, Joseph.  aAdorno, Theodor.  aAravamudan. Srinivas.  aAusten, Jane.  aBakhtin, Mikhail.  aBrosse, Monique.  aCabot, Sebastian.  aCaptain Courageous.  aCorinne.  aEdwards, Philip.  aEnlightenment.  aEpic and Empire.  aEthiopian Romance.  aFictions of the Sea.  aFlanders, Moll.  aFrankfurt School.  aFulton, Robert.  aGautier, Maurice-Paul.  aGreat Southern Continent.  aHard Times.  aHeliodorus.  aHerbert, William Henry.  aIntrepid lunar module.  aJameson, Fredric.  aJohnson, Captain.  aKnight, Diana.  aLem, Stanislas.  aMaiorino, Giancarlo.  aNeuromancer.  aOriental tales.  abourgeois reason.  acannibals.  acapitalism.  achase theme.  aclipper ships.  aconjecture.  acyberfiction.  acybernetics.  adanger.  adomestic novel.  adomestic themes.  aendeavor.  aglobalization.  ahistorical nov